Types of Set Operations in PostgreSQL
🟢 1. UNION

👉 Combines results and removes duplicates

SELECT name FROM students
UNION
SELECT name FROM teachers;
✅ Key Points:

Removes duplicate rows

Columns must match (same count + compatible types)

🟡 2. UNION ALL

👉 Combines results but keeps duplicates

SELECT name FROM students
UNION ALL
SELECT name FROM teachers;
✅ Difference from UNION:

Faster ✅

Does NOT remove duplicates ❌

🔵 3. INTERSECT

👉 Returns common data from both queries

SELECT name FROM students
INTERSECT
SELECT name FROM alumni;
✅ Use Case:

Find common users

Matching records

🔴 4. EXCEPT (PostgreSQL uses EXCEPT)

👉 Returns data from first query NOT present in second

SELECT name FROM students
EXCEPT
SELECT name FROM alumni;
✅ Use Case:

Find missing records

Difference between datasets

